page.text: The proposed Old Heritage development is projected to consist of 12,000 square feet
of either office building or retail development with access to Crossbow Circle
adjacent to Route 220 (Franklin Road) in Roanoke County, Virginia. A traffic impact
analysis was performed by AECOM for the site in order to determine how site
development would impact traffic operations. As the specific land use for the
development is unknown at this time it was determined that the Land Use of
Pharmacy with Drive-Thru window would generate the greatest amount of new trips,
so to be conservative this was the land use used for traffic analysis.
The proposed development will have one full-access driveway on Crossbow Circle
approximately 350 feet from its intersection with Route 220. The property is
currently zoned residential and will be rezoned to commercial to accommodate the
proposed development. The project is expected to be completed by 2013.
The traffic impact analysis study area consisted of three signalized intersections of
Route 220 with Old Rocky Mount Road, Crossbow Circle, and Valley Ave/Southern
Hills Drive as well as the proposed unsignalized driveway. AM and PM peak hour
traffic data was collected for existing intersections. The design year of 2019 was
analyzed for complete development buildout, which is six years after development
completion. Based on historical data in the site vicinity it was assumed that the
background growth rate on the roadway network is 0.5%.
Traffic operations analysis using Synchro software was performed to determine the
impacts of site development on the study intersection. Synchro generates delay and
queuing projections as well as a Level of Service (LOS) designation based on average
delays. The LOS designation is a qualitative representation of operating conditions
on a scale of A (free-flow travel) to F (high congestion, forced traffic flow).
The signalized intersections currently have a number of lane groups which operate at
LOS E or below. Given the traffic volumes on Route 220, this is not unexpected.
Acceptable Levels of Service D or better are projected to occur for all movements
where projected site traffic is added in the 2019 design year. All turning movements
for the development entrance are projected to operate at LOS A. Therefore, the
proposed development is not projected to significantly impact traffic operations and
no mitigation is recommended based on the projected land use.
The County of Roanoke has requested that a traffic impact analysis (TIA) be
performed for the proposed Old Heritage development to be located on Crossbow
Circle in Roanoke County, Virginia. AECOM agreed to perform the TIA on behalf
of Old Heritage, LLC. The area is currently zoned as residential but will be rezoned
to commercial in order to accommodate the proposed development. The development
is projected to consist of either an office building or retail development. The project
is expected to be completed by 2013.
The purpose of this TIA is to determine if the traffic volumes expected to be
generated by this proposed development will have significant impacts on traffic
operations in the area. This TIA includes traffic data collection, a trip generation
analysis, projected site trip distribution and a capacity analysis for existing and both
2019 “No-Build” and “Build” conditions within a pre-established study area.
Prior to beginning this TIA a study area consisting of four intersections was defined
and agreed upon by the County of Roanoke. AM and PM peak hour turning
movement traffic counts, geometrical data, signal timings and other pertinent
information were collected at the existing intersections. The study intersections are
1. Route 220 (Franklin Road SW) and Old Rocky Mount Rd.
3. Route 220 and Valley Ave./Southern Hills Dr.
4. Crossbow Circle and Proposed Development Entrance
Figure 1 shows the study area and the location of the proposed development. The
current site plan shows one full access driveway for the development accessible off of
Crossbow Circle approximately 350 feet from the intersection with Route 220.
Turning movement traffic counts for the study area were conducted on Thursday
January 12, 2012 during expected peak periods of travel which included the hours of
7:00 AM to 9:00 AM and 4:00 PM to 6:00 PM. Existing peak hour traffic volumes
Data at each intersection was collected by Peggy Malone and Associates.
From the traffic data collection on Thursday January 12, 2012 the morning and
evening peak hours of travel (AM/PM Peak Hours) were determined for each of the
intersections. The AM peak hour in the study area was found to occur between 7:15-
8:15 AM and the PM peak hour occurs between 4:45-5:45 PM. The peak hour factors
were also calculated for every approach at each intersection. These peak hour
volumes served as base values for forecasting future “No Build” and “Build”
conditions. All peak hour count data is displayed in Appendix A.
A design year of 2019 (2013 build date plus 6 years) was assumed for this study.
Historical volume data for Route 220 in the site vicinity shows negative growth from
2006 to 2010, but to be conservative a 0.5% growth rate was assumed for all roads.
Planned background developments in the study area were also considered. The South
Peak (formerly Slate Hill) development north of the study area, a Bojangles at the Old
Rocky Mount Road/Route 220 intersection and the Clearbrook Lane development
south of the study area were identified as developments that are expected to impact
traffic volumes on Route 220 through the study area. Traffic Impact Studies
completed for these key developments were consulted in order to incorporate new
vehicle trips projected along Route 220 through the study intersections.
The 0.5% growth rate was compounded over six years and background traffic
associated with the aforementioned developments was added to existing count data to
generate projections for 2019 “No Build” volumes. The Food Lion grocery store on
Route 220 between Crossbow Circle and Old Rocky Mount Road in the study area
closed after traffic data was collected, but traffic volumes were not reduced in order
to reflect the potential for redevelopment of a similar magnitude. Projected 2019 “No
Build” volumes are shown in Figure 3.

text.b: 3.3 Trips Generated from Old Heritage Development

page.text: A trip generation analysis was performed for the proposed Old Heritage development
with the goal of forecasting the number of additional trips that the new development
would route through the intersections included within the study area.
Using the ITE Trip Generation Manual, 8
Edition, trips were calculated for both
AM and PM peak hours based on the type of land uses the development is expected to
include. The current site plan for the development includes 12,000 square feet (sf) of
either office building or retail space. As the exact usage of the site has not been
determined at this time, various possible uses were considered and the one with the
highest amount of trips generated was used in the analysis to represent the most
conservative condition. It was determined that the land use of Pharmacy/Drugstore
with Drive-Through Window (ITE Land Use Code 881) is a potential land use for the
site and would generate the highest number of trips, so this land use was utilized for
trip generation. If the land use changes and is projected to generate a higher number
of trips, additional study should be performed.
Tables 1 and 2 present the forecast of total trips expected to be generated during the
AM and PM peak hours assuming a pharmacy with drive-through. For a
Pharmacy/Drugstore with Drive-Through land use, the Trip Generation Manual
provides average rates but not regression equations, so the average rates were used.

is a pharmacy with drive-through window due to the nature of the development and a
location adjacent to Route 220. For a pharmacy with drive-through, the ITE Trip
Generation Handbook suggests a pass-by trip rate of 49% for the PM peak hour based
on empirical data. Similarly, ITE studies further indicated that the primary trip
percentage for drive-through pharmacies is often no more than 50% (where the
development is the ultimate purpose of a vehicle on the roadway network and not just
While the site driveway is on Crossbow Circle and not Route 220, the close proximity
of the busy arterial to the site is expected to result in diverted link trips turning off of
Route 220 and then returning to Route 220 to continue in the same direction for the
50% estimate of non-primary site trips. Therefore, a general reduction in new site
trips of 50% was applied to trip generation estimates in order to account for pass-by
and diverted link trips, with the 50% reduction being represented by vehicles already
traveling by the site on Route 220. There were no trip reduction considerations for
AM trips considering there was no rate proposed for the AM Peak Hour by the ITE
After calculating the number of entering and exiting trips expected to be generated by
the development during the peak hour travel periods, trip distribution factors were
then projected for turning movements at each intersection within the study area.
These factors were determined based on existing traffic tendencies observed in the
field as well as taking into consideration location of site access and the routes drivers
would likely be expected to use when entering or exiting the Old Heritage
development. Based on the projected location of the single access point, all site traffic
is expected to access the site via Crossbow Circle. Trip distribution percentages were
determined for entering and exiting site traffic during the AM and PM peak hours.
The projected trip distribution percentage is shown graphically on Figure 4. The trip
distribution was applied to the total site traffic projected to be generated by the
development in order to determine new turning movements approaching and
departing from the development after completion. These projected site trips are

movement of all four intersections by beginning with 2019 “No Build” volumes,
applying the trip distribution to the results from the trip generation analysis to project
site traffic, and adjusting the volumes to account for pass-by/diverted link trips. 2019
“Build” condition volumes are shown in Figure 7.

Using the Synchro 7.0 and SimTraffic software, a traffic model for the study area was
prepared based on the geometrical layout of the study area intersections and signal
timings obtained from the City of Roanoke. Capacity analyses were then performed
for the study area to determine delays, queuing and Level of Service during the AM
and PM peak hours for 2012 Existing conditions, 2019 “No Build” conditions, and
Level of Service (LOS) is a qualitative representation of traffic operating conditions
between LOS A and LOS F that considers stability of flow, driver comfort, delays
and other factors. LOS A represents free flow conditions and LOS F represents
extreme congestion and conditions where demand exceeds capacity. In urban areas
such as this, LOS D is typically considered to be the threshold for acceptable traffic
operations. Any impacts associated with the Old Heritage development that would
cause a lane group to deteriorate to LOS E or F may warrant mitigation.
In addition to Synchro analysis, ten randomly seeded SimTraffic microsimulations
were performed for the study network. SimTraffic accounts for the interaction
between adjacent intersections and can generate results that better reflect the
functionality of a signalized intersection corridor as featured in this study. SimTraffic
generates LOS and delay projections, and is also able to record and report maximum
queues observed during a simulation period for each lane group. The Maximum
Queue reported by a calibrated microsimulation model is often a more accurate
reflection of field conditions in comparison to Synchro’s 95
The capacity analysis results reported in this study will reflect LOS and delay as
generated by Synchro and the average of the maximum queue recorded by
SimTraffic. Ultimately, comparisons between the capacity analyses were drawn from
intersection delays, LOS and queuing lengths to determine the impacts the Old
Heritage development will be expected to have on traffic operations of the previously
Synchro and SimTraffic reports for 2012 existing conditions are included in
Appendix B. For each lane group, the LOS, delay and SimTraffic maximum queues
from 10 simulations under existing conditions are summarized in Table 3.
The intersection of Route 220 and Crossbow Circle is currently operating at LOS F
during the AM peak. All other intersections are currently operating at an overall LOS
D or better during both peak periods. During the AM and PM peak hour there are a
number of movements which operate at LOS E or below under existing conditions.

Synchro and SimTraffic reports for 2019 “Build” conditions are included in
Appendix D. The LOS, delay and maximum queues for each lane group under
“Build” conditions are summarized below in Table 5.
Lane groups at LOS D or above for existing conditions are projected to remain as
such except for the westbound approach to the intersection of Route 220 and
Crossbow Circle during the AM peak hour, which is projected to operate at LOS E.
With multiple lane groups operating at LOS E or below in existing conditions the
additional traffic that would be generated by the proposed development makes a
minimal impact. With one exception, all lane groups operating at LOS D or better
under existing conditions are projected to continue operating effectively under
“Build” conditions. The westbound Crossbow Circle approach to Route 220 is
projected to deteriorate to LOS E during the AM peak, but no site traffic is projected
to be added to this lane group, and the maximum queue from SimTraffic modeling is
not significantly higher than for “No Build” conditions and is not projected to impact
the site driveway. Therefore, it is projected that new traffic generated by the
proposed development will not significantly impact traffic operations in the study
area during either of the studied peak periods.
Turn lane warrant analysis was performed at the proposed site driveway to the
development on Crossbow Circle by consulting Appendix F of the VDOT Road
Design Manual and using 2019 “Build” condition peak hour volumes. From VDOT’s
Appendix F, Figure 3-26 was used for right turn lane warrants (two lane roadway)
and Figure 3-9 (<40 mph design speed, two lane roadway, ~30% left turns) was used
for left turn lane warrants during each peak hour. These graphs are shown in
Appendix E. The conceptual site plan showing the proposed location of the site
driveway is included as Appendix F.
For peak hour volumes a minimum of 20 right turns warrants a taper and 40 turns
warrants a turn lane, but minimal right turn entries into the site are projected.
Therefore, a right turn lane is not required. For left turn warrants, the advancing and
opposing volumes projected on Crossbow Circle under “Build” conditions do not
warrant a left turn lane in either peak hour. However, provision of turn lanes would
minimize the risk of site turning movements causing delays and queues that could
interfere with Crossbow Circle through traffic and potentially impact Route 220 due
to the proximity of the site driveway to the mainline and the traffic signal
Site traffic and new turning movements onto and off of Route 220 are expected to
have the most impact to the study area on the Crossbow Circle intersection. FR-300
police reports of crash data from the last three years of available data within 500 feet
of this signalized intersection were provided by VDOT. Figure 8 is a graphical
representation of the crash data, and shows each of the crashes by type and by
As shown in Figure 8, results indicated that 21 recorded crashes occurred at or near
this location between 2008 and 2010. A majority of the crashes in the site vicinity are
rear-end crashes (13 of 21), which is typical along signalized corridors. Eight of the
Of the 21 crashes in the last three years of available data, only 7 are associated
directly with vehicles approaching or traveling through the Crossbow Circle
intersection with Route 220. Only one angle crash has occurred over the last three
years at the intersection. Four of the seven crashes were rear-ends, one was a
sideswipe and one involved a vehicle striking an animal.
No fatalities have been recorded at the intersection in the last three years of available
data. None of the 21 crashes within the last three years of available data were
attributed directly to traffic on Crossbow Circle. If sight distance and access
management requirements are met, site development is not expected to significantly
impact safety or crash rates, as there is no direct site access onto or off of Route 220
and no recent history of crashes on Crossbow Circle. Therefore, there are no
significant safety concerns associated with the intersection of Route 220 with
Crossbow Circle or with development of the site.
While they are not directly associated with the Crossbow Circle intersection, it is
important to note that two fatal accidents have occurred along the study corridor in
the last three years. On November 17, 2010 on Route 220 between Electric Road
(Route 419) and Valley Avenue/Southern Hills Drive a motorist was killed in a
collision with a tractor trailer. On October 15, 2011 at the Old Rocky Mount Road
intersection, a motorist was also killed pulling onto Route 220 in a collision with a
tractor trailer. This crash occurred before the intersection was signalized.
Traffic operational analysis for the “Build” condition after development of the Old
Heritage site indicates that only one lane group in the study area is expected to
deteriorate below an acceptable LOS D during the AM peak hour, but site
development is not projected to add traffic to this movement. Therefore,
development of this site is not expected to impact traffic operations in the study area
No geometric improvements are recommended in association with the Old Heritage
development. Should a significant change occur to the scope of the development or
the site plan, it is recommended that any changes be accounted for with additional
traffic analysis to verify that no mitigation is required.
